Price by categorical variables¶

In [12]:
# List of categorical variables
categorical_variables = ['neighbourhood_group','room_type']

# Loop through each categorical variable
for var in categorical_variables:
    # Calculate the median price for each category in the dataset
    median_prices = merged_data.groupby(var)['price'].mean().sort_values()

    # Plot bar plot with median prices
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    ax = median_prices.plot(kind='bar', color='grey')
    plt.title(f'Median Price by {var}')
    #plt.xlabel(var.replace('_', ' ').title())  # Replace underscores with spaces and capitalize words
    plt.ylabel('Median Price')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Add data labels to the bars
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(f'${p.get_height():.2f}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha='center', va='center',
                    xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points')

    plt.show()

Distribution of price by neighbourhood and room types¶

In [20]:
# Grouping data by 'neighbourhood_group' and 'room_type' and calculating the mean price
med_price = merged_data.groupby(['neighbourhood_group', 'room_type'])['price'].median().reset_index()

# Define custom colors for each bar
custom_colors = ['#FF5A5F', '#00A699', '#FC642D', '#484848', '#767676']

# Plotting the bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(data=med_price, x='neighbourhood_group', y='price', hue='room_type', palette=custom_colors)
plt.title('Median Listing Price by Neighbourhood and Room Type')
plt.xlabel('Neighbourhood')
plt.ylabel('Median Price')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Add data labels to the bars
for p in ax.patches:
    # Round the height of the bar to two decimal places
    height = round(p.get_height())
    if height != 0:
        ax.annotate(f'${height}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., height), ha='center', va='center', 
                    xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points', fontsize=10)

plt.legend(title='Room Type', loc='upper left')
plt.show()

#Step 1: Feature Scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()

In [70]:
#Step 2: Dimensionality reduction

# Create a PCA instance
pca = PCA().fit(scaled_data)

# Calculate cumulative explained variance ratio
cumulative_variance_ratio = np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)

# Plot cumulative explained variance ratio
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance_ratio) + 1), cumulative_variance_ratio, marker='o', linestyle='-',color='#FF5A5F')
plt.xlabel('Number of Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Variance Explained')
plt.title('Cumulative Variance Explained by Principal Components')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In [71]:
#Taking the first 6 PCs and transforming the data as they explain >80% of the variance
reduced_data = pca.fit_transform(scaled_data)
reduced_data = reduced_data[:,[0,1,2,3,4,5]]
In [72]:
# Step 3: Choosing the Number of Clusters
inertia = []
x_axis = list(range(1,15))

for x in x_axis:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=x,random_state=0,max_iter = 1000,init = 'k-means++')
    kmeans.fit(reduced_data)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)  

#Elbow plot to get value of K
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,7))    

ax.set_title('The elbow method')
ax.set_ylabel('Inertia')
ax.set_xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.plot(x_axis, inertia,color='#00A699')
plt.show()
In [74]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Initialize a list to store silhouette scores
silhouette_scores = []

# Define a range of K values to try
k_values = range(2, 11)  # Example range from 2 to 10

# Compute silhouette scores for each K
for k in k_values:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0, max_iter = 1000, init = 'k-means++')
    kmeans.fit(reduced_data) 
    labels = kmeans.labels_
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(reduced_data, labels))
    
# Plot silhouette scores
plt.plot(k_values, silhouette_scores, color='#FC642D')
plt.title('Silhouette Score for Different Values of K')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.xticks(k_values)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In [77]:
# Visualize Clusters K-means Model

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# Rename the labels for clarity
cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_

# Plotting the 3D scatter plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Define colors for each cluster
colors =   ['#FF5A5F','#767676', '#00A699', '#FC642D', '#484848','lightgrey','red'] 

# Scatter plot for each cluster
for cluster, color in zip(np.unique(cluster_labels), colors):
    indices = cluster_labels == cluster
    ax.scatter(reduced_data[indices, 0], 
               reduced_data[indices, 1], 
               reduced_data[indices, 2], 
               label=f'Cluster {cluster}', s=50, c=color)

# Adding labels to the plot
ax.set_xlabel('PC 1')
ax.set_ylabel('PC 2')
ax.set_zlabel('PC 3')

# Adding a legend
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

## Function to remove numbers, symbols and characters to clean text
import re

def clean_text(text):
    # Remove numbers, symbols, and other non-alphabetic characters
    text = str(text)
    cleaned_text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z\s]', '', text)
    return cleaned_text

In [112]:
# Calculate inertia for K-Means
kmeans_inertia = kmeans.inertia_

# There's no inertia attribute for Gaussian Mixture Model, as it's not applicable
# Instead, you can calculate the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center

# Define a function to calculate the sum of squared distances for GMM
def calculate_gmm_inertia(model, data):
    labels = model.predict(data)
    centers = model.means_
    distances = np.array([np.linalg.norm(x - centers[labels[i]])**2 for i, x in enumerate(data)])
    return np.sum(distances)

gmm_inertia = calculate_gmm_inertia(gaussian_model, reduced_data)

print("Inertia for K-Means:", kmeans_inertia)
print("Inertia for Gaussian Mixture Model:", gmm_inertia)

Inertia for K-Means: 180272.85836652876
Inertia for Gaussian Mixture Model: 190514.77378064682

Functions for model evaluation¶

In [120]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

def calculate_cv_rmse(model, X, y, cv=10):
    MSE_CV_scores = -cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=cv, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=-1)
    RMSE_CV = np.sqrt(MSE_CV_scores.mean())
    return RMSE_CV
In [121]:
#For evaluating the models
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score

def evaluate_model(model, X_test, y_test):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    return mae, mse, r2
